Customer Service Representatives are the spokes persons for the establishment. Even though  Perelandra has a diverse customer and customer service community base, I don’t believe the establishment practices diversity and inclusion. Nor do they train reps on tolerance and handling varying belief systems; especially when it doesn’t always co mingle with their own truths. Its a human thing to not notice when you are behaving in ways that assumes it’s ok to operate in fear of people who are different, which only promotes ignorant attitudes.  I  have experienced fear based relations between reps and customers. Reps can’t grow into being mentally healthy within a fear induced environment. It can be damaging to the psyche when the rep doesn’t have the tools to handle the most toughest situations. I have found that management and reps aren’t consistent with operating in healthy ways to create a synergistic environment. One thing that I have encountered recently, and that is a real problem, is homophobic behaviors displayed by some of the reps. A biased ignorant and immature attitude creates a breeding ground of fear. Little by little things can potential grow into a big situation that gets out of hand. Ive done the boundary work to stop engaging with individuals who hold those attitudes within the establishment, because Im simply there to shop nothing more. But it is the experience that matters most. Give your reps real people skills training that tackles the work place phobias and help them to develop healthy attitudes. Treat them fairly and see real change take effect. While I love the majority of my produce experience, and interaction with a few reps, we must uphold policies across the board to recognize others for their differences and treat them fairly; especially with customers and between staff relationships.  While the produce at  Perelandra is consistently good, some of my past experiences shopping at Perelandra natural foods include: almost purchasing expired products, witnessing bad fruit rotting underneath other fruit, and a lack of maintenance for the utensils used for the fruits and nuts located in the back of the store. I talked to management about these issues and the only one remaining  produce issue is the lack of maintenance for the utensils used for nuts and fruits. Its a little daunting to consider using a dirty utensil that’s on display for scooping up food that I would eventually be eating. Thats a germ issue. I’ve decided to be proactive and use a plastic bag to scoop up the nuts and fruits instead of the tools they offer. That way the issue is resolved on my end. With regard to produce, I love what I buy and the prices are great.  On a different note: At one time, I noticed how cold customer service reps looked at the counters and spoke to a manager about a heating issue.  productive mindsets are in question under duress working environments and conditions. Reps simply can’t create a great customers service experience when they aren’t getting proper heat. There has been little to no real change since I spoke to management about the lack of heat in the store. It up to reps to speak up for themselves, especially when they are being mistreated.  Whats very difficult to imagine is that somewhere in the upper echelon of the store’s management is where the problem lies. When reps normally operate a certain way it’s always a reflection of who is at the top and lack of managements awareness of ongoing issues that are bubbling. It takes an immense skill sets to endorse a more conscious atmosphere. The real issue usually lies somewhere at the top.   In my opinion, a health food store should also promote healthy behaviors, offering their staff the skill sets to develop a mindset that empowers them to grow as healthy human beings.

This is the best natural foods store in NYC! They have the best product selection and the most genuinely caring and helpful staff. (It’s independently owned and they actually pay their employees fairly too - there are no super rich CEOs here for a change! Business with a conscience! How refreshing!) Shopping here is supporting local business and this store is a rare treasure among an ever-expanding sea of corporate behemoths. What speaks the loudest is where you choose to spend your money, so I choose to keep it local and support the businesses of honest, hardworking New Yorkers. My experience for many years has been that this store is a cut above the rest. This is why Brooklyn is awesome. Highly recommended.
